Here's how to implement this in .NET MAUI Shell:

## 1. Override `OnBackButtonPressed` on your page

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Fire-and-forget the async confirmation
            Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
            {
                bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                    "Unsaved Changes",
                    "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                    "Discard", "Stay");

                if (leave)
                    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            });

            return true; // Cancel the default back navigation
        }

        return base.OnBackButtonPressed(); // Allow normal navigation
    }
}
```

## 2. Custom "Cancel" back button in the toolbar

In your XAML:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{x:Null}">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior Command="{Binding CancelCommand}"
                           TextOverride="Cancel"
                           IconOverride="" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 3. ViewModel command with confirmation

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave) return;
    }

    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

## Key points

| Concern | Mechanism |
|---------|-----------|
| Hardware/swipe back | `OnBackButtonPressed()` → return `true` to cancel |
| Custom button text | `BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride` |
| Hide default arrow | Set `IconOverride=""` (empty string) |
| Programmatic nav | Gate with `DisplayAlert` before `GoToAsync("..")` |

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` only fires for the Android hardware/gesture back button. On iOS swipe-back, you may also need to disable the gesture by setting `Shell.BackButtonBehavior` with `IsEnabled="True"` and routing all back navigation through your command. On iOS, the interactive pop gesture can be disabled via a platform-specific handler if needed.
